abor used, and actually change the economics of visits.=E2=80=9D
Every single company in healthcare wants to own the =E2=80=9Cfront door=E2=
=80=9D of healthcare and be the point of contact for patients when they nee=
d anything.
In America, the spend per patient is much higher than in emerging markets, =
which means the immediate financial opportunity is greater. But the America=
n market also presents more competition, more deep-pocketed incumbents, and=
 more onerous regulation. Emerging markets present an opportunity to serve =
billions of people with new solutions built from the ground up.=C2=A0
In many ways, emerging markets present a better opportunity for healthcare =
startups:
Regulators are welcoming of insurance penetration, given the low levels hig=
hlighted above and the fact that insurance is the best way to stabilize a g=
rowing middle class.
Emerging markets are often less controlled by incumbents and special intere=
sts.=C2=A0
There is a large pool of customers who were previously unserved or deeply u=
nderserved. Globally, over 1 billion people entered the middle class over t=
he past ten years.
Healthcare spend is growing faster in emerging markets than developed ones.=
=C2=A0
According to the WHO, in middle income countries, including Antara=E2=80=99=
s first market, Kenya, health spending rose 6.3% a year between 2000 and 20=
17, nearly double the global 3.9% rate, and outpacing the broader emerging =
market economies=E2=80=99 5.9% growth.=C2=A0
Reinsurers estimate that there is a $250 billion premium gap for the emergi=
ng middle class globally, as insurance penetration rises from current 1-3% =
levels up to at least 8-10%. The opportunity for HealthTech in emerging mar=
kets has double-tailwinds: 1) the economies are growing more quickly than d=
eveloped countries, and 2) healthcare and insurance spend as a percentage o=
f the total economy is growing.=C2=A0
Zooming in on Africa, the Afrobility podcast (a go-to for me) did an episod=
e on African HealthTech in October that you should listen to if you=E2=80=
=99re interested in learning more.=C2=A0
The hosts, Olumide Ogunsanwo and Bankole Makanju, highlight some incredible=
 statistics. First, while Africa has 25% of the global disease burden, less=
 than 1% of healthcare spend occurs on the continent. Second, the average l=
ife expectancy in Sub-Saharan Africa is 61 versus 77 in China and 78 in the=
 United States. Third, Kenya spends $76 per citizen per year on healthcare =
compared to over $10,000 in the US.
But spend only tells part of the story. According to Olumide and Bankole, H=
ealthcare in Africa faces real challenges:=C2=A0
Talent and Brain Drain. Africa has a shortage of healthcare workers (less t=
han 10% of what they need for primary care). There are 8,000 Nigerian docto=
rs in the US compared to 35,000 Nigerian doctors in Nigeria. HealthTech com=
panies need to figure out a way to get more out of fewer doctors.=C2=A0
Logistics and Cold Chain. Drugs and vaccines require cold storage and trans=
portation, which can be difficult when electricity is often unreliable.=C2=
=A0
Insurance. As covered above, a tiny percentage of people are insured.=C2=A0
There is a clear need for new solutions, and new companies are working on t=
hem. HealthTech as a percentage of African venture funding grew from 2-3% i=
n 2018 to 8-9% in 2019. The Afrobility hosts cite examples across a few cat=
egories: Patients, Payors (I=E2=80=99m going with the spelling that Antara =
uses), Providers, Manufacturers, Distributors, and others. The most relevan=
t are:=C2=A0
Babyl: Spun out from Babylon Health in the UK, Bably provides chatbot consu=
ltation, ML-based diagnosis, doctor visit booking, and live video and audio=
 sessions.=C2=A0
mPharma: The Ghana-based company manages prescription drug inventory for ph=
armacies to make drugs more affordable. mPharma has raised $55 million in t=
he past five years, including $17 million in 2020.
BIMA Health: Founded in Stockholm in 2010, BIMA offers mobile-delivered mic=
roinsurance and serves ten countries, including three in Africa. Members ca=
n buy insurance on their phone with airtime credits and book appointments w=
ith doctors. The company has raised $200 million.=C2=A0
Zipline: The San Francisco-based company has raised $233 million to develop=
 drones that can deliver medication to remote areas.=C2=A0
MTN Ayo: Like BIMA, Africa=E2=80=99s leading telco offers microinsurance th=
at people can purchase with airtime credits. They can submit claims directl=
y through WhatsApp.=C2=A0
These examples show that there is investor appetite for Africa-focused Heal=
thTech companies. Each one though, tackles only a small slice of the proble=
m. The hosts cite China=E2=80=99s Ping An or Brazil=E2=80=99s Doctor Consul=
tor as examples of what HealthTech could be in Africa. Then Bankole said so=
mething that made my ears perk up:=C2=A0
The ones that I=E2=80=99ve seen scale in these emerging markets have been v=
ertically integrated.=C2=A0
Antara Health [https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFkEFuxCAMRU8zLCMgYQYWLLr=
pNZAJToKaQAROo_T0ZWYqVbJsydbX9_sjEM65XHbPldizObp2tAnPuiIRFnZULC4GK-5S92owLN=
ghCK00i9VNBXGDuFoqB7L98GscgWJOLwXnUrHF9kaaCQIaYcw4Dug98jtMCqa78YMwb184QsQ0o=
sVvLFdOyFa7EO311n_c5Ger8zw7SAQFFoSVlm7MW1uzaCWXgguhRXtQ6U50nOc-4vQwPwC3gW-z=
7OrhK8H49VSxYlMmn0tMczt_LbDh-jo0BNfmdqRIl8MEfsXwpqN3SC9eN2PC0sILDqhFI7h5aG6=
0fPzRNPxe9L0yg2LNOeSmSv-mv59DgAU] is building a Natively Integrated company=
 to change how healthcare happens in emerging markets by helping each healt=
h professional serve more people and making insurance affordable for a wide=
r swath of the population.=C2=A0
Antara Health: The Natively Integrated Healthcare Company
Antara feels like what Teladongo would build if they could start fresh. It=
=E2=80=99s reimagining healthcare by leveraging telemedicine, data science,=
 and emerging markets payors=E2=80=99 and regulators=E2=80=99 willingness t=
o try new models. They=E2=80=99re building virtual-first primary care, a ne=
w model of healthcare that integrates life and health protection using data=
=2E=C2=A0
It=E2=80=99s a Natively Integrated Healthcare Company. In The Rise of the N=
atively Integrated Company [https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFkM2OhSAMhZ=
_mstPw4w8sWMxmXsOgVCWDYACvcZ5-enUxSdMSmpPT70ymwBLTpfeYC_m0oVw76ABn9lAKJHJkS=
IOzmnVcirZRxOrGMtlK4vIwJ4DNOK9LOoDsx-jdZIqL4VZQyluyamUlFbSbJVN87iwD2Slqusl2=
IEzf2cfXHNZBmEDDG9IVAxCv11L2_BJfL_6NdZ5nvZvp59rqKW74Mfq44DBTqURVVqiSy1DF-X4=
HvOMN_qpcQMaEoLZC2W7CRZzmlDPKmGSI1Mqa1ZRG4WDu1a8xr4ZuC6_zMeaCfh83knSIZYzJhQ=
XXP6vZwN8LhB5wbkdw5RogmNGDffIoT6x3QsMCAe4rBlMwTEZVL6mSvFcPPwYmmBCtalqCzjaiK=
vyb_gFrbpGF], I wrote that Natively Integrated Companies (NICs):=C2=A0
Leverage technology to integrate the customer-impacting components of their=
 value chain, build relationships with customers, and are willing to commit=
 capital to build products that resonate with them.
The Natively Integrated model works particularly well for problems that hav=
e been historically difficult to solve due to challenges with coordination =
and incentive alignment among different stakeholders. It=E2=80=99s why I=E2=
=80=99m so bullish on Apt [https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxVkMFuhSAQRb_=
msdMAyhMXLLrpbxiUUUkRCI6vsV_fqSZtmgCzuBnOvXeyCEsqp8lpR_bzDHhmMBE-9wCIUNixQx=
m8M-IpdaPanjnTOqGVZn4f5gKwWR8MlgNYPsbgJ4s-xWuDc6nYap5uVDN3cwOj5JIr4Sbed8L1s=
rNKt-3NtYfzECcw8IJypggsmBUx74_m7SHf6cSEYyo-LvV-jDva6aOe0kZCpmszVrhCFQn_gnBW=
PlK0Qvlc5ejLkDKUSo9k25ALwYXQgvIoXYua89R4mLv-y9pHy7dF_kOwYn7ZJH-sdoNwCZR4oLk=
d0eM5QLRjAHeXgXenVz3DAhEuL4NFalJQfs17Lbv-Dk9tNaJpVN8qRmSXaCv-Qb8BA--Qqg]=E2=
=80=99s approach to real estate development.=C2=A0
In Antara=E2=80=99s case, the company=E2=80=99s Health Navigation is the mi=
ssing layer to primary care. Telemedicine, e-triage, care coordination, rem=
ote monitoring, digital health counseling, and digital therapeutics all hav=
e been proven to improve health, but in piecemeal, struggle or fail to full=
y address patient needs and realize their potential. Antara=E2=80=99s solut=
ion is a strategic slice of all that, integrated.
Antara simplifies all of the complexity to a single trusted source that gui=
des a patient=E2=80=99s healthcare journey, and leverages technology in ord=
er to scale the human touch. It even has virtual care doctors on-staff, and=
 can cover 50-70% of primary care cases within Antara=E2=80=99s care. The c=
ompany specializes in chronic condition management and puts mortality at th=
e forefront as the objective, asking the one question that every health pro=
fessional should be asking: Are we improving and extending patients=E2=80=
=99 lives?
To learn more about Antara=E2=80=99s solution, early traction, business mod=
el, and risks:=20
If you=E2=80=99re an accredited investor and want to learn more, you can ch=
eck out the Not Boring Syndicate on AngelList.=C2=A0
